	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>How to tell if a pin is an input or output?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I've got an ASIC circa 1990 (so NMOS or CMOS probably?) with some NC pins with traces that lead off the board for testing. I'd like to know if they're inputs or outputs but I don't know how to do this safely with common parts.
<br />
<br />Can I just touch VCC through a current limited LED to the pin to see if it sinks current? If it does, that makes it either an input or a low output, right? But then what?
<br />
<br />Thanks!

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Bregalad</b> [ Mon Dec 17, 2007 10:04 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I guess the trick is to connect the pin to ground trough a moderately low resistance (something like 470 ohms), then repeat with connecting it to high level supply. If current in either case has been moderately high, then it's output, if the current is always very low no matter what you do the pin in input. Don't know if this answers your question.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

